FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - MOZAMBIQUE (02): (TETE) CATTLE, NOT SEROTYPED, WOAH
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 3 Aug 2022
Source: WOAH, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2022 [edited]
https://wahis.woah.org/#/report-info?reportId=58149


Foot and mouth disease virus, Mozambique
----------------------------------------
General information
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 24 Jul 2022
Confirmed: 1 Aug 2022
Reported: 3 Aug 2022
Reason for notification: recurrence
Last occurrence: 13 Aug 2020
Causal agent: foot and mouth disease virus
Subtype: not typed
Nature of diagnosis: clinical
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: Chinheche, Kambulatsitsi, Moatize, Tete
Date of start of the outbreak: 24 Jul 2022
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Cattle / 9175 / 104 / 0 / 0 / 0 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: introduction of new live animals, illegal movement of animals

Epidemiological comments: the disease affects cattle of both sexes and all ages. The affected animal show excessive salivation, difficulty walking, eruptive lesions in the mouth, and lameness. No deaths were reported.

Control measures
Domestic control measures applied: ante and post-mortem inspections; movement control; surveillance within the restricted zone; surveillance outside the restricted zone

Wild control measures applied: movement control

Diagnostic test results: not available

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the WOAH report at the source URL above.]

--
communicated by:
ProMED

[Two outbreaks of FMD type O were previously reported in cattle at Nhantha (16 Mar 2022) and Nsadzo (14 May 2022), Mualadzi, Chifunde, province of Tete.

